04441nam a22005415i 9780804764070DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047640707 a10.1515/97808047640702doi  a(DE-B1597)582420  a(OCoLC)1312727199  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBH201.A395 1999eb 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a1951 aAgamben, Giorgio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPotentialities :bCollected Essays in Philosophy /cGiorgio Agamben; ed. by Daniel Heller-Roazen. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMeridian: Crossing Aesthetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tEditor’s Note -- tEditor’s Introduction: “To Read What Was Never Written” -- tPart One. Language -- t1. The Thing Itself -- t2. The Idea of Language -- t3. Language and History: Linguistic and Historical Categories in Benjamin’s Thought -- t4. Philosophy and Linguistics -- t5. Kommerell, or On Gesture -- tPart Two. History -- t6. Aby Warburg and the Nameless Science -- t7. Tradition of the Immemorial -- t8. *Se: Hegel’s Absolute and Heidegger’s Ereignis -- t9. Walter Benjamin and the Demonic: Happiness and Historical Redemption -- t10. The Messiah and the Sovereign: The Problem of Law in Walter Benjamin -- tPart Three. Potentiality -- t11. On Potentiality -- t12. The Passion of Facticity -- t13. Pardes : The Writing of Potentiality -- t14. Absolute Immanence -- tPart Four. Contingency -- t15. Bartleby, or On Contingency -- tNotes -- tIndex of Names -- tCrossing Aesthetics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book collects fifteen major philosophical essays written over a period of more than twenty years by acclaimed Italian philosopher Giorgio Agamben. The volume opens with an introduction in which the editor situates Agamben's work with respect to both the history of philosophy and contemporary European thought. The essays that follow articulate a series of theoretical confrontations with privileged figures in the history of philosophy, politics, and criticism, from Plato to Spinoza, Aristotle to Deleuze, Carl Schmitt to Benjamin, Hegel to Aby Warburg, and Heidegger to Derrida. Three fundamental concepts organize the collection as a whole: language, in the sense not of particular statements but rather the very taking place of speech, the pure fact of language's existence; history, as it appears from a perspective in which tradition, transmission, and memory reach their messianic fulfillment; and potentiality, understood as a fundamental problem of metaphysics, ethics, and the philosophy of language. All these topics converge in the final part of the book, in which Agamben offers an extensive reading of Melville's short story "Bartleby the Scrivener" as a work that puts potentiality and actuality, possibility and reality, in an altogether new light.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy -- Poststructuralism and Phenomenology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh1 aHeller-Roazen, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107042110 cprintz978080473277240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476407040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804764070/original  a978-3-11-070421-1  Stanford University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles